    149 Chapter 3: Fluid Dynamics Multiple Charges with Varying Ignition Main Index The PARAMETER JWLDET in SOL 700 is available to define the nature of the interrelation of the explosives described by EOSJWL . With this PARAMETER , active explosive materials are ignited as specified by the user and are not triggered by other explosive materials . As an example, the blast wave created by two explosive charges is shown in Figure 3-25 and Figure 3-26. For simplicity; a 2-D calculation is set-up with two cylindrical charges represented as by the “Static Detonation” model. (The axes of the cylinders are perpendicular to the plane of the figure). The mesh boundaries are rigid walls, by default. The full SOL 700 input file is shown after the figures.PARAM, JWLDET, OPTION OPTION MEANING LINK Multiple denotations with EOSJWL are LINKED . The detonation wave of one explosive can ignite another explosive. PARAM, JWLDET, OPTION NOLINK Multiple denotations with EOSJWL are NOT LINKED . The detonation wave of one explosive cannot ignite another explosive. TDET is set to -1 for elements that have no JWL material. The NOLINK option is only valid with true JWL materials - not valid for the “Static Detonation/Ideal Gas” model. Thus, setting this parameter as NOLINK prevents “sympathetic ignition”. Each charge ignites at the specified TDET in its own DETSPH card. Default NOLINK

    155 Chapter 3: Fluid Dynamics Nonuniformity with MESH,BOX Main Index Nonuniformity with MESH,BOX MESH,BOX allows the user to create nonuniform block meshes. These meshes were traditionally constructed only by preprocessors such as Patran. A uniform Euler block consists of a number of planes in each direction. These are at fixed distances. MESH, BOX has a functionality that allows full control over the locations of the planes. This functionality is activated by defining BIAS entries and using them on the MESH entry. The BIAS entries specify the locations of the planes. Problem Description If the explosive is small and the object far away, it is often necessary to use a non-uniform mesh that is fine near the explosive and coarse further away. This example problem illustrates the use of nonuniform meshes created by MESH,BOX . To model the blast, ideal gas will be considered. The initial radius of the sphere will be R0=0.2 m. Ideal gas model Blast Products (r<R0) Environment (r>R0) The simulation will be run for 9 ms.     Demonstration Guide (SOL 700) Explicit Nonlinear Water Waves with Cyclic Flow Boundaries162 Main Index Water Waves with Cyclic Flow Boundaries Problem Description Cyclic flow boundaries are useful for turbo machine simulations with rotational symmetry. In this example, it is used to model the propagation of a water wave moving through a infinitely long channel. A water wave inside a rectangular box is created by initializing the Euler mesh with a MATINI surface. Furthermore, a constant initial velocity is put on the water that causes the water to move from left to right. Since the water wave extends across the whole length of the Euler domain, water will move out of the Euler domain leading to a fast degradation of the water wave. To prevent this and to keep the water wave moving, use is made of cyclic flow boundaries. The water will move out at the right and will re-enter the Euler domain at the left . As a result the water-wave can be maintained and will not significantly degrade. This problem will be modeled with water and void. The water properties are : Reference density = 1000 kg/m3 Bulk modulus K = 2.2e+6 Pa The bulk modulus has been scaled down to allow for shorter run times. This is acceptable since the compressibility effects can be ignored here. The initial shape of the water wave is shown in Figure 3-28. Figure 3-28 Initial Water Level

The inflow of FLOWC 4 will be taken from the outflow of FLOWC5. This allows to maintain the water wave as it exists at the right side of the Euler domain and allows it re-enters again at the left.
